# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: focus-peaking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] B&H opened in 1973 as a storefront film shop at 17 Warren Street in Tribeca, taking its name from the initials of owners Blimie and Herman Schreiber.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] Later in the 1970s, B&H moved to 119 West 17th Street between Sixth and Seventh Avenues in the Photo District and began to expand its stock to a wider range of film and photography products.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In the 1990s, the company began selling various electronics, including computers, lighting, and audio equipment.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 1997, the store moved to its present location.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The owner of the company, Herman Schreiber, and many of the store's employees are observant Satmar Hasidic Jews.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The company’s only brick-and-mortar store is located in Manhattan at 420 Ninth Avenue at the intersection with West 34th Street.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The store is closed on Shabbat, most Jewish holidays, and Christmas.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] Although the B&H website is accessible on Shabbat, checkout and processing of online orders are unavailable during that time (from sundown Friday evening till Saturday evening) along with Jewish holidays according to local (New York) time.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2007, B&H opened a second floor above its original sales floor making a total of 70,000 sq ft (6,500 m2) of sales space.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] That same year, B&H moved its offices to 440 9th Avenue in Manhattan.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] As the company has grown, it expanded its office presence to accommodate sales, customer service, buying, marketing, and various back office functions; these functions are housed in 150,000 square feet of office space.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The store has an extensive conveyor belt system that runs along the ceiling.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2015, B&H added an Apple authorized shop to the computer department with an assortment of Apple products.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] There is an Apple employee in shop to assist and consult.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2016, Vaio announced that they signed a contract with B&H photo video to offer their products.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2017, B&H moved their warehouses in Brooklyn to their fulfillment center of over 500,000 square feet located in Florence, New Jersey.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2023, B&H Photo Video celebrated its 50th anniversary with the inaugural Bild Expo (named after the Yiddish word for "image"), held on September 6–7 at the Javits Center in New York City.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] 4. the Creative Production stage or filmmaking, videography, and editing.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In addition to educational experiences, the expo included a 100,000+ square-foot Gear Expo with more than 130 creative technology brands.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The event also celebrated the 100th anniversary of 16mm filmmaking with a special Kodak 16mm Film Workshop.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] Also in 2023, as part of the company’s 50th anniversary celebration, B&H sold custom LEGO models of their flagship store.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2025, B&H Photo Video hosted its second Bild Expo on June 17–18, again at the Javits Center in New York City and again was free to attend.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The 2025 Bild Expo featured six stages, over 100 speakers, over 250 exhibitors, and hands-on workshops.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] There were reports of up to 50,000 attendees over the two days.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] Some of the talks featured Pulitzer Prize-winning photojournalist Lynsey Addario, conservation photographer Cristina Mittermeier, author Scott Kelby, filmmaker Drex Lee, cinematographer Sarina Soriano, cinematographer Ed Lachman, headshot photographer Peter Hurley, and photojournalist Chris Burkard.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] There was also a Women in Media panel with actress and content creator Shuang Hu, Outshine Talent CEO Barbara Jones, Verizon Head of Creators Lina Renzina, and The Luupe CEO Keren Sachs.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] Major brands included Sony, Nikon, Apple, Leica, Adobe, GoPro, Fujifilm and Canon.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] Unlike typical merchant-based trade shows, Bild Expo does not intend to make any profit from the event itself.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The apparent success and demand of attendees at Bild Expo is speculated to also be a result of the decline of similar recent camera and film expos in New York City, which gave Bild Expo the opportunity to satisfy audience demand.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] Moreover, the conference also dedicated one-third of its conference sessions to content creation to bring in a typically younger audience to complement B&H's core photography audience.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2019, B&H Photo launched the B&H *Payboo* store credit card through Synchrony Financial only for use at B&H including their website and store.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] When using the card, B&H collects and remits the appropriate sales tax but instantly rebates the same amount to the customer.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2022, the card was relaunched through Comenity Capital Bank and gave customers the choice of a sales tax benefit or financing of up to 12 months on qualifying purchases.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2013, the B&H Wilderness Photo Competition awarded two prizes, one based on a professionally judged vote and one from a popular choice vote.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The competition included categories such as land mammals, aquatic, birds, and landscape/scenery.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2018, B&H sponsored Bushwick Stories, a documentary workshop for young storytellers created by the Bushwick Film Festival.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] For many years, B&H has sponsored NYC Salt, a program that offers intensive photography training to NYC high school students.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] B&H also sponsors programs and fellowships at BRIC, the largest presenter of free cultural programming in Brooklyn.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] B&H has worked with partners, including Intel, to donate tech equipment to NYC public school classrooms.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] During the COVID-19 pandemic, B&H organized "Days of Appreciation" for health care workers at Lenox Hill Hospital and other NYC hospitals.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In October 2007, it was reported that B&H Photo agreed to a US$4.3 million settlement in response to claims of discrimination against Hispanic workers.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In November 2009, B&H Photo faced a lawsuit, initiated by four women, for allegedly violating New York City and New York State human rights laws with their hiring practices.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The lawsuit, which aimed for class action status, sought $19 million in compensatory and punitive damages to discourage similar future practices.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2011, B&H was involved in a lawsuit concerning claims of discrimination against Hispanic workers.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In September 2021, the New York Supreme Court dismissed a lawsuit filed by the Attorney General of New York State claiming the company knowingly avoided paying millions in New York sales taxes, finding that B&H had not acted improperly.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2015, B&H's Google Play app was named the "Best Mobile Shopping App" at the Mobile Shop Conference.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2016, Consumer Reports awarded B&H Photo its No.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] 1 Top Rating for Best Electronics Retailer, and in 2018, named it the leading online consumer electronics retailer.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In May 2018, B&H was named by Forbes Magazine as one of America's Best Midsize Employers for 2018.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] The Forbes recognition was based on independent employee surveys conducted by Forbes.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2020, the company was included on Forbes' “America’s Best Employers By State” list.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2018, B&H's consumer website was recognized as the Best for User Experience of any e-commerce company by the Baymard Institute.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] They were also ranked #1 in the Institute's mobile usability benchmark of the 50 highest grossing U.S. e-commerce sites.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] B&H Photo has won two Webby Awards in the How-to, Explainer & DIY video category; for *The Art of Street Photography with Hugh Brownstone* in 2023, and Ira Block's *The Colours of Cuba* in 2024.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] In 2025, B&H Photo was listed in *Newsweek*'s America's Most Loved Brands 2025 and America's Best of the Best 2025.
[src:focus-peaking/b-h-photo] B&H was listed in *USA TODAY*'s Most Trusted Brands in 2025 and 2026.
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] Until February 2010, *DPReview* did not score cameras numerically, but used a six-level rating system (from best to worst: Highly Recommended, Recommended, Above Average, Average, Below Average, Poor).
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] The site now scores all cameras and lenses using up to 11 categories (which in turn are based on "nearly 60 aspects of camera performance and specification").
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] Two new discretionary awards ('Gold' and 'Silver') were introduced at the same time as the scoring system.
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] Although the vast majority of its published reviews are of digital cameras, *DPReview* also publishes occasional reviews of printers, software, photography books, accessories and mobile imaging devices.
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] The original founder, Phil Askey, is no longer involved in the day-to-day running of the site.
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] The company directly employs 14 full-time workers.
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] Askey was followed as general manager by Simon Joinson, who took on the role in 2010.
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] The current manager is Scott Everett who joined *DPReview* in 2011 as a Product Manager.
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] On March 21, 2023, *DPReview* announced that it would cease operations, but that its website would remain available as an archive.
[src:focus-peaking/digital-photography-review] On June 20, 2023, *DPReview* was acquired by Gear Patrol and resumed operations.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A **digital single-lens reflex camera** (**digital SLR** or **DSLR**) is a digital camera that combines the optics and mechanisms of a single-lens reflex camera with a solid-state image sensor and digitally records the images from the sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The reflex design scheme is the primary difference between a DSLR and other digital cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In the reflex design, light travels through the lens and then to a mirror that alternates to send the image to either a prism, which shows the image in the optical viewfinder, or the image sensor when the shutter release button is pressed.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The viewfinder of a DSLR presents an image that will not differ substantially from what is captured by the camera's sensor, as it presents it as a direct optical view through the main camera lens rather than showing an image through a separate secondary lens.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] DSLRs largely replaced film-based SLRs during the 2000s.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Major camera manufacturers began to transition their product lines away from DSLR cameras to mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras beginning in the 2010s.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Smith invented charge-coupled semiconductor devices, which can be used as analog storage registers and image sensors.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A CCD (Charge-Coupled Device) imager provides a low-noise analog image signal, which is digitized when used in a digital camera.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] For their contribution to digital photography, Boyle and Smith were awarded the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 1973, Fairchild developed a 100 x 100 pixel interline CCD image sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This CCD was used in the first commercial CCD camera, the Fairchild MV-100, which was introduced in late 1973.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 1974, Kodak scientists Peter Dillon and Albert Brault used this Fairchild CCD 202 image sensor to create the first color CCD image sensor by fabricating a red, green, and blue color filter array that was registered and bonded to the CCD.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 1975, Kodak engineer Steven Sasson built the first portable, battery-operated digital still camera, which used a zoom lens from a Kodak Super 8mm movie camera and a monochrome Fairchild 100×100 pixel CCD.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The first prototype filmless SLR camera was publicly demonstrated by Sony in August 1981.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The Sony Mavica (a magnetic still video camera) used a color-striped 2/3” format CCD sensor with 280K pixels, along with analog video signal processing and recording.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The Mavica electronic still camera employed a TTL single-lens reflex viewfinder, as shown in the graphic from a June 1982 Sony press release.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] It recorded FM-modulated analog video signals on a newly developed 2” magnetic floppy disk, dubbed the "Mavipak".
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The disk format was later standardized as the "Still Video Floppy", or "SVF", so the Sony Mavica was the first "SVF-SLR" to be demonstrated, but it was not a D-SLR since it recorded analog video images rather than digital images.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Starting in 1983, many Japanese companies demonstrated prototype SVF cameras, including Toshiba, Canon, Copal, Hitachi, Panasonic, Sanyo, and Mitsubishi.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The Canon RC-701, introduced in May 1986, was the first SVF camera (and the first SVF-SLR camera) sold in the US.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] It employed an SLR viewfinder and included a 2/3” format color CCD sensor with 380K pixels.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] It was sold along with removable 11-66mm and 50-150mm zoom lens.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Over the next five years, many other companies began selling SVF analog electronic cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] These included the monochrome Nikon QV-1000C SVF-SLR camera, introduced in 1988, which had a specialized QV-mount (a non-F-mount) for interchangeable QV Nikkor lenses.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 1986, the Kodak Microelectronics Technology Division developed a 1.3 MP CCD image sensor, the first with more than 1 million pixels.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 1987, this sensor was integrated with a Canon F-1 film SLR body at the Kodak Federal Systems Division to create an early DSLR camera.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The digital back monitored the camera body battery current to sync the image sensor exposure to the film body shutter.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Digital images were stored on a tethered hard drive and processed for histogram feedback to the user.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This camera was created for the U.S. government, and was followed by several other models intended for government use and eventually Kodak DCS, a commercial DSLR series launched in 1991.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 1995, Nikon co-developed the Nikon E series with Fujifilm.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The E series included the Nikon E2/E2S, Nikon E2N/E2NS and Nikon E3/E3S, with the E3S released in December 1999.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In the late 1990s, Sony introduced the "Digital Mavica" series of consumer digital cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Unlike the original analog Mavica, the Digital Mavica cameras recorded JPEG compressed image files on standard 3½-inch magnetic floppy discettes (meant to simplify camera-to-computer data transfer) and did not have an SLR viewfinder.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The D1's body was similar to Nikon's professional 35 mm film SLRs, and it had the same Nikkor lens mount, allowing the D1 to use Nikon's existing line of AI/AIS manual focus and AF lenses.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Although Nikon and other manufacturers had produced digital SLR cameras for several years prior, the D1 was the first professional digital SLR that displaced Kodak's then-undisputed reign over the professional market.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Over the next decade, other camera manufacturers entered the DSLR market, including Canon, Kodak, Fujifilm, Minolta (later Konica Minolta, and ultimately acquired by Sony), Pentax (whose camera division is now owned by Ricoh), Olympus, Panasonic, Samsung, Sigma, and Sony.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In January 2000, Fujifilm announced the FinePix S1 Pro, the first consumer-level DSLR.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In November 2001, Canon released its 4.1-megapixel EOS-1D, the brand's first professional digital body.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2003, Canon introduced the 6.3-megapixel EOS 300D SLR camera (known in the United States and Canada as the Digital Rebel and in Japan as the Kiss Digital) with an MSRP of US$999, aimed at the consumer market.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Its commercial success encouraged other manufacturers to produce competing digital SLRs, lowering entry costs and allowing more amateur photographers to purchase DSLRs.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2004, Konica Minolta released the Konica Minolta Maxxum 7D, the first DSLR with in-body image stabilization which later become standard in Pentax, Olympus, and Sony Alpha cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In early 2008, Nikon released the D90, the first DSLR to feature video recording.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Since then, all major companies have offered cameras with this functionality.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Over time, the number of megapixels in imaging sensors has increased steadily, with most companies focusing on high ISO performance, speed of focus, higher frame rates, the elimination of digital 'noise' produced by the imaging sensor, and price reductions to lure new customers.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In June 2012, Canon announced the first DSLR to feature a touchscreen, the EOS 650D/Rebel T4i/Kiss X6i.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Although this feature had been widely used on both compact cameras and mirrorless models, it had not made an appearance on a DSLR until the 650D.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The DSLR market is dominated by Japanese companies, and the top five manufacturers are Japanese: Canon, Nikon, Olympus, Pentax, and Sony.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Other manufacturers of DSLRs include Mamiya, Sigma, Leica (Germany), and Hasselblad (Swedish).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2007, Canon edged out Nikon with 41% of worldwide sales to the latter's 40%, followed by Sony and Olympus, each with approximately 6% market share.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In the Japanese domestic market, Nikon captured 43.3% to Canon's 39.9%, with Pentax a distant third at 6.3%.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2008, Canon's and Nikon's offerings took the majority of sales.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2010, Canon controlled 44.5% of the DSLR market, followed by Nikon with 29.8% and Sony with 11.9%.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] For Canon and Nikon, digital SLRs were their biggest source of profit in the early 2010s.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Canon's DSLRs brought in four times the profits of their compact digital cameras, while Nikon earned more from DSLRs and lenses than from any other product.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Olympus and Panasonic have since exited the DSLR market and now focus on producing mirrorless cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2013, after a decade of double-digit growth, DSLR (along with MILC) sales were down 15 per cent.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This may be due to some low-end DSLR users choosing to use a smartphone instead.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The market intelligence firm IDC predicted that Nikon would be out of business by 2018 if the trend continued, although this did not come to pass.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Regardless, the market has shifted from being driven by hardware to software, and camera manufacturers have not been keeping up.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Beginning in the 2010s, major camera manufacturers began to transition their product lines away from DSLR cameras to mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras (MILCs).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In September 2013, Olympus announced they would stop the development of DSLR cameras and focus on the development of MILCs.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Nikon announced they were ending production of DSLRs in Japan in 2020, followed by similar announcements from Canon and Sony.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2021, mirrorless cameras began to outsell DSLRs for the first time since their introduction; this trend has continued as all major camera brands other than Pentax have ceased production of new consumer DSLR models as of 2025.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Contax, Fujifilm, Kodak, Panasonic, Olympus, Sigma, Sony, and Samsung all previously produced DSLRs but now either exclusively offer non-DSLR systems or have left the camera market entirely.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Currently, DSLRs are widely used by consumers and professional still photographers.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Well-established DSLRs currently offer a wide variety of dedicated lenses and other equipment and can be found for lower prices than newer mirrorless cameras; however, the majority of companies that historically produced DSLRs have since ceased production in favor of mirrorless systems.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Mainstream DSLRs (in full-frame or smaller image sensor format) are produced by Nikon and Pentax.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Phase One, Hasselblad, and Mamiya Leaf produce expensive, high-end medium-format DSLRs, including some with removable sensor backs.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Konica Minolta's line of DSLRs was purchased by Sony.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Like SLRs, DSLRs typically use interchangeable lenses with a proprietary lens mount.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A movable mechanical mirror system is switched down (to precisely a 45-degree angle) to direct light from the lens over a matte focusing screen via a condenser lens and a pentaprism/pentamirror to an optical viewfinder eyepiece.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Most entry-level DSLRs use a pentamirror instead of the traditional pentaprism.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Focusing can be manual, by twisting the focus on the lens; or automatic, activated by pressing half-way on the shutter release or a dedicated auto-focus (AF) button.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] To take an image, the mirror swings upwards in the direction of the arrow, the focal-plane shutter opens, and the image is projected and captured on the image sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] After these actions, the shutter closes, the mirror returns to the 45-degree angle, and the built-in drive mechanism re-tensions the shutter for the next exposure.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Compared with the newer concept of mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras, this mirror/prism system is the characteristic difference, providing direct, accurate optical preview with separate autofocus and exposure metering sensors.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Essential parts of all digital cameras are some electronics like amplifiers, analog-to-digital converters, image processors, and other microprocessors for processing the digital image, performing data storage, and/or driving an electronic display.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] DSLRs typically use autofocus based on phase detection.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This method allows the optimal lens position to be calculated rather than "found", as would be the case with autofocus based on contrast maximization.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Phase-detection autofocus is typically faster than other passive techniques.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] As the phase sensor requires the same light going to the image sensor, it was previously only possible with an SLR design.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, with the introduction of focal-plane phase-detect autofocusing in mirrorless interchangeable lens cameras by Sony, Fuji, Olympus, and Panasonic, cameras can now employ both phase detect and contrast-detect AF points.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Digital SLR cameras, along with most other digital cameras, generally have a mode dial to access standard camera settings or automatic scene-mode settings.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Sometimes called a "PASM" dial, they typically provide modes such as program, aperture-priority, shutter-priority, and full manual modes.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Scene modes vary from camera to camera, and these modes are inherently less customizable.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] They often include landscape, portrait, action, macro, night, and silhouette, among others.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, these different settings and shooting styles that "scene" mode provides can be achieved by calibrating certain settings on the camera.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A method to prevent dust from entering the chamber by using a "dust cover" filter right behind the lens mount was used by Sigma in its first DSLR, the Sigma SD9, in 2002.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Olympus used a built-in sensor cleaning mechanism in its first DSLR that had a sensor exposed to air, the Olympus E-1, in 2003 (all previous models each had a non-interchangeable lens, preventing direct exposure of the sensor to outside environmental conditions).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Several Canon DSLR cameras rely on dust reduction systems based on vibrating the sensor at ultrasonic frequencies to remove dust from the sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Interchangeable lenses for SLRs and DSLRs are built to operate correctly with a specific lens mount that is generally unique to each brand.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A photographer will often use lenses made by the same manufacturer as the camera body (for example, Canon EF lenses on a Canon body) although there are also many independent lens manufacturers, such as Sigma, Tamron, Tokina, and Vivitar, that make lenses for a variety of different lens mounts.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] There are also lens adapters that allow a lens for one lens mount to be used on a camera body with a different lens mount, but with often reduced functionality.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Many lenses are mountable, "diaphragm-and-meter-compatible", on modern DSLRs, and on older film SLRs that use the same lens mount.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, when lenses designed for 35 mm film or equivalently sized digital image sensors are used on DSLRs with smaller sized sensors, the image is effectively cropped and the lens appears to have a longer focal length than its stated focal length.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Most DSLR manufacturers have introduced lines of lenses with image circles optimised for the smaller sensors and focal lengths equivalent to those generally offered for existing 35 mm mount DSLRs, mostly in the wide-angle range.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] These lenses tend not to be completely compatible with full-frame sensors or 35 mm film because of the smaller imaging circle and with some Canon EF-S lenses, interfere with the reflex mirrors on full-frame bodies.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Since 2008, manufacturers have offered DSLRs which offer a movie mode capable of recording high definition motion video.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A DSLR with this feature is often known as an HDSLR or DSLR video shooter.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The first DSLR introduced with an HD movie mode, the Nikon D90, captures video at 720p24 (1280x720 resolution at 24 frame/s).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Other early HDSLRs capture video using a nonstandard video resolution or frame rate.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] For example, the Pentax K-7 uses a nonstandard resolution of 1536×1024, which matches the imager's 3:2 aspect ratio.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The Canon EOS 500D (Rebel T1i) uses a nonstandard frame rate of 20 frame/s at 1080p, along with a more conventional 720p30 format.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In general, HDSLRs use the full imager area to capture HD video, though not all pixels (causing video artifacts to some degree).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Compared with the much smaller image sensors found in the typical camcorder, the HDSLR's much larger sensor yields distinctly different image characteristics.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] HDSLRs can achieve much shallower depth of field and superior low-light performance.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, the low ratio of active pixels (to total pixels) is more susceptible to aliasing artifacts (such as moiré patterns) in scenes with particular textures, and CMOS rolling shutter tends to be more severe.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Furthermore, due to the DSLR's optical construction, HDSLRs typically lack one or more video functions found on standard dedicated camcorders, such as autofocus while shooting, powered zoom, and an electronic viewfinder/preview.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] These and other handling limitations prevent the HDSLR from being operated as a simple point-and-shoot camcorder, instead of demanding some level of planning and skill for location shooting.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The Canon EOS 5D Mark II (with the release of firmware version 2.0.3/2.0.4.) and Panasonic Lumix GH1 were the first HDSLRs to offer 1080p video at 24fps, and since then the list of models with comparable functionality has grown considerably.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The rapid maturation of HDSLR cameras has sparked a revolution in digital filmmaking (referred to as "DSLR revolution"), and the "Shot On DSLR" badge is a quickly growing phrase among independent filmmakers.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Canon's North American TV advertisements featuring the Rebel T1i have been shot using the T1i itself.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Other types of HDSLRs found their distinct application in the field of documentary and ethnographic filmmaking, especially due to their affordability, technical and aesthetical features, and their ability to make observation highly intimate.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] An increased number of films, television shows, and other productions are utilizing the quickly improving features.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] One such project was Canon's "Story Beyond the Still" contest that asked filmmakers to collectively shoot a short film in 8 chapters, with each chapter being shot over a short period of time and a winner was determined for each chapter.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] After 7 chapters the winners collaborated to shoot the final chapter of the story.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Due to the affordability and convenient size of HDSLRs compared with professional movie cameras, The Avengers used five Canon EOS 5D Mark II and two Canon 7D to shoot the scenes from various vantage angles throughout the set and reduced the number of reshoots of complex action scenes.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Manufacturers have sold optional accessories to optimize a DSLR camera as a video camera, such as a shotgun-type microphone, and an External EVF with 1.2 million pixels.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Early DSLRs lacked the ability to show the optical viewfinder's image on the LCD screen – a feature known as live preview.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Live preview is useful in situations where the camera's eye-level viewfinder cannot be used, such as underwater photography where the camera is enclosed in a plastic waterproof case.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2000, Olympus introduced the Olympus E-10, the first DSLR with live preview – albeit with an atypical fixed lens design.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In late 2008, some DSLRs from Canon, Nikon, Olympus, Panasonic, Leica, Pentax, Samsung and Sony all provided continuous live preview as an option.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Additionally, the Fujifilm FinePix S5 Pro offers 30 seconds of live preview.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] On almost all DSLRs that offer live preview via the primary sensor, the phase-detection autofocus system does not work in the live preview mode, and the DSLR switches to a slower contrast system commonly found in point-and-shoot cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] While even phase detection autofocus requires contrast in the scene, strict contrast-detection autofocus is limited in its ability to find focus quickly, though it is somewhat more accurate.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In 2012, Canon introduced hybrid autofocus technology to the DSLR in the EOS 650D/Rebel T4i, and introduced a more sophisticated version, which it calls "Dual Pixel CMOS AF", with the EOS 70D.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The technology allows certain pixels to act as both contrast-detection and phase-detection pixels, thereby greatly improving autofocus speed in live view (although it remains slower than pure phase detection).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] While several mirrorless cameras, plus Sony's fixed-mirror SLTs, have similar hybrid AF systems, Canon is the only manufacturer that offers such technology in DSLRs.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A new feature via a separate software package introduced from Breeze Systems in October 2007, features live view from a distance.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The software package is named "DSLR Remote Pro v1.5" and enables support for the Canon EOS 40D and 1D Mark III.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Image sensors used in DSLRs come in a range of sizes.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The very largest are the ones used in "medium format" cameras, typically via a "digital back" which can be used as an alternative to a film back.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Because of the manufacturing costs of these large sensors, the price of these cameras is typically over $1,500 and easily reaching $8,000 and beyond as of February 2021.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] "Full-frame" is the same size as 35 mm film (135 film, image format 24×36 mm); these sensors are used in DSLRs such as the Canon EOS-1D X Mark II, 5DS/5DSR, 5D Mark IV and 6D Mark II, and the Nikon D5, D850, D750, D610 and Df.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Most lower-cost DSLRs use a smaller sensor that is APS-C sized, which is approximately 24×16 mm, slightly smaller than the size of an APS-C film frame, or about 40% of the area of a full-frame sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Leica offers an "S-System" DSLR with a 30×45 mm array containing 37 million pixels.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This sensor is 56% larger than a full-frame sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The resolution of DSLR sensors is typically measured in megapixels.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] More expensive cameras and cameras with larger sensors tend to have higher megapixel ratings.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A larger megapixel rating does not mean higher quality.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Low light sensitivity is a good example of this.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] When comparing two sensors of the same size, for example, two APS-C sensors one 12.1 MP and one 18 MP, the one with the lower megapixel rating will usually perform better in low light.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This is because the size of the individual pixels is larger, and more light is landing on each pixel, compared with the sensor with more megapixels.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This is not always the case, because newer cameras that have higher megapixels also have better noise reduction software, and higher ISO settings to make up for the loss of light per pixel due to higher pixel density.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The lenses typically used on DSLRs have a wider range of apertures available to them, ranging from as large as f/0.9 to about f/32.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Lenses for smaller sensor cameras rarely have true available aperture sizes much larger than f/2.8 or much smaller than f/5.6.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] To help extend the exposure range, some smaller sensor cameras will also incorporate an ND filter pack into the aperture mechanism.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The apertures that smaller sensor cameras have available give much more depth of field than equivalent angles of view on a DSLR.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] For example, a 6 mm lens on a 2/3″ sensor digicam has a field of view similar to a 24 mm lens on a 35 mm camera.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] At an aperture of f/2.8, the smaller sensor camera (assuming a crop factor of 4) has a similar depth of field to that 35 mm camera set to f/11.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The angle of view of a lens depends upon its focal length and the camera's image sensor size; a sensor smaller than 35 mm film format (36×24 mm frame) gives a narrower angle of view for a lens of a given focal length than a camera equipped with a full-frame (35 mm) sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] As of 2017, only a few current DSLRs have full-frame sensors, including the Canon EOS-1D X Mark II, EOS 5D Mark IV, EOS 5DS/5DS R, and EOS 6D Mark II; Nikon's D5, D610, D750, D850, and Df; and the Pentax K-1.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The scarcity of full-frame DSLRs is partly a result of the cost of such large sensors.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Medium format size sensors, such as those used in the Mamiya ZD among others, are even larger than full-frame (35 mm) sensors, and capable of even greater resolution, and are correspondingly more expensive.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The impact of sensor size on the field of view is referred to as the "crop factor" or "focal length multiplier", which is a factor by which a lens focal length can be multiplied to give the full-frame-equivalent focal length for a lens.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Typical APS-C sensors have crop factors of 1.5 to 1.7, so a lens with a focal length of 50 mm will give a field of view equal to that of a 75 mm to 85 mm lens on a 35 mm camera.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The smaller sensors of Four Thirds System cameras have a crop factor of 2.0.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] While the crop factor of APS-C cameras effectively *narrows* the angle of view of long-focus (telephoto) lenses, making it easier to take close-up images of distant objects, *wide*-angle lenses suffer a reduction in their angle of view by the same factor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] DSLRs with "crop" sensor size have slightly more depth-of-field than cameras with 35 mm sized sensors for a given angle of view.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The amount of added depth of field for a given focal length can be roughly calculated by multiplying the depth of field by the crop factor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Shallower depth of field is often preferred by professionals for portrait work and to isolate a subject from its background.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] On July 13, 2007, FujiFilm announced the FinePix IS Pro, which uses Nikon F-mount lenses.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This camera, in addition to having live preview, has the ability to record in the infrared and ultraviolet spectra of light.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In August 2010 Sony released series of DSLRs allowing 3D photography.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] It was accomplished by sweeping the camera horizontally or vertically in Sweep Panorama 3D mode.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The picture could be saved as ultra-wide panoramic image or as 16:9 3D photography to be viewed on BRAVIA 3D television set.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In the reflex design scheme, the image captured on the camera's sensor is also the image that is seen through the viewfinder.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Light travels through a single lens and a mirror is used to reflect a portion of that light through the viewfinder – hence the name "single-lens reflex".
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] While there are variations among point-and-shoot cameras, the typical design exposes the sensor constantly to the light projected by the lens, allowing the camera's screen to be used as an electronic viewfinder.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, LCDs can be difficult to see in very bright sunlight.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Compared with some low-cost cameras that provide an optical viewfinder that uses a small auxiliary lens, the DSLR design has the advantage of being parallax-free: it never provides an off-axis view.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A disadvantage of the DSLR optical viewfinder system is that when it is used, it prevents using the LCD for viewing and composing the picture.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Some people prefer to compose pictures on the display – for them, this has become the de facto way to use a camera.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Depending on the viewing position of the reflex mirror (down or up), the light from the scene can only reach either the viewfinder or the sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Therefore, many early DSLRs did not provide "live preview" (i.e., focusing, framing, and depth-of-field preview using the display), a facility that is always available on digicams.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Today most DSLRs can alternate between live view and viewing through an optical viewfinder.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The larger, advanced digital cameras offer a non-optical electronic through-the-lens (TTL) view, via an eye-level electronic viewfinder (EVF) in addition to the rear LCD.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The difference in view compared with a DSLR is that the EVF shows a digitally created image, whereas the viewfinder in a DSLR shows an actual optical image via the reflex viewing system.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] An EVF image has the lag time (that is, it reacts with a delay to view changes) and has a lower resolution than an optical viewfinder but achieves parallax-free viewing using less bulk and mechanical complexity than a DSLR with its reflex viewing system.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Optical viewfinders tend to be more comfortable and efficient, especially for action photography and in low-light conditions.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Compared with digital cameras with LCD electronic viewfinders, there is no time lag in the image: it is always correct as it is being "updated" at the speed of light.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This is important for action or sports photography, or any other situation where the subject or the camera is moving quickly.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Furthermore, the "resolution" of the viewed image is much better than that provided by an LCD or an electronic viewfinder, which can be important if manual focusing is desired for precise focusing, as would be the case in macro photography and "micro-photography" (with a microscope).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] An optical viewfinder may also cause less eye-strain.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, electronic viewfinders may provide a brighter display in low light situations, as the picture can be electronically amplified.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] DSLR cameras often have image sensors of much larger size and often higher quality, offering lower noise compared to compact cameras, which is useful in low light.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] This advantage is shared by mirrorless cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] For a long time, DSLRs offered faster and more responsive performance, with less shutter lag, faster autofocus systems, and higher frame rates.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Around 2016–17, some mirrorless camera models started offering competitive or superior specifications in these aspects.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The downside of these cameras being that they do not have an optical viewfinder, making it difficult to focus on moving subjects or in situations where a fast burst mode would be beneficial.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Still, compact digital cameras are not suited for action, wildlife, sports, and other photography requiring a high burst rate (frames per second).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Bridge cameras provide some degree of manual control over the camera's shooting modes, and some even have hot shoes and the option to attach lens accessories such as filters and secondary converters.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] DSLRs typically also have fully automatic shooting modes.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] DSLRs have a larger focal length for the same field of view, which allows the creative use of depth of field effects.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, small digital cameras can focus better on closer objects than typical DSLR lenses.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] The sensors used in current DSLRs — "full-frame" which is the same size as 35mm film, APS-C, and Four Thirds System — are much larger than most digital cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Entry-level compact cameras typically use sensors known as 1/2.3″, which is 3% the size of a full-frame sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] There are fixed-lens cameras — such as bridge cameras, premium compact cameras, or high-end point-and-shoot cameras — that offer sensors larger than 1/2.3″, but many still fall short of the larger sizes widely found in DSLRs.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] These premium compacts are often comparable to entry-level DSLRs in price, with a smaller sensor being a tradeoff for the size and weight savings.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Unlike DSLRs, most digital cameras lack the option to change the lens.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Instead, most compact digital cameras are manufactured with a zoom lens that covers the most commonly used fields of view.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Having fixed lenses, they are limited to the focal lengths they are manufactured with, except for what is available from attachments.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Manufacturers have attempted (with increasing success) to overcome this disadvantage by offering extreme ranges of focal length on models known as superzooms, some of which offer far longer focal lengths than readily available DSLR lenses.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] There are now available perspective-correcting (PC) lenses for DSLR cameras, providing some of the attributes of view cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Nikon introduced the first fully manual PC lens in 1961.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Recently, however, some manufacturers have introduced advanced lenses that shift and tilt and are operated with automatic aperture control.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, since the introduction of the Micro Four Thirds system by Olympus and Panasonic in late 2008, mirrorless interchangeable lens cameras are now widely available.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Hence, the option to change lenses is no longer unique to DSLRs.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Cameras for the micro four-thirds system are designed with the option of a replaceable lens, and lenses that conform to this proprietary specification are accepted.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Cameras for this system have the same sensor size as the Four-Thirds System but do not have the mirror and pentaprism to reduce the distance between the lens and sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Panasonic released the first Micro Four Thirds camera, the Lumix DMC-G1.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Several manufacturers have announced lenses for the new Micro Four Thirds mount.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In contrast, older Four-Thirds lenses can be mounted with an adapter (a mechanical spacer with front and rear electrical connectors and its own internal firmware).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A similar mirror-less interchangeable lens camera with an APS-C-sized sensor was announced in January 2010: the Samsung NX10.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] On 21 September 2011, Nikon announced with the Nikon 1 a series of high-speed MILCs.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] A handful of rangefinder cameras also support interchangeable lenses.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Six digital rangefinders exist: the Epson R-D1 (APS-C-sized sensor), the Leica M8 (APS-H-sized sensor), both smaller than 35 mm film rangefinder cameras, and the Leica M9, M9-P, M Monochrom and M (Typ 240) (all full-frame cameras, with the Monochrom shooting exclusively in black-and-white).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] In common with other interchangeable lens designs, DSLRs must contend with potential sensor contamination by dust particles when the lens is changed (though recent dust reduction systems alleviate this).
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Digital cameras with fixed lenses are not usually subject to dust from outside the camera settling on the sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] DSLRs generally have more significant cost, size, and weight.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] They also have louder operation, due to the SLR mirror mechanism.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] Sony's fixed mirror design manages to avoid this problem.
[src:focus-peaking/dslrs] However, that design has the disadvantage that the mirror diverts some of the light received from the lens, and thus, the image sensor receives about 30% less light compared with other DSLR designs.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The purpose of detecting sharp changes in image brightness is to capture important events and changes in properties of the world.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] In the ideal case, the result of applying an edge detector to an image may lead to a set of connected curves that indicate the boundaries of objects, the boundaries of surface markings as well as curves that correspond to discontinuities in surface orientation.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Thus, applying an edge detection algorithm to an image may significantly reduce the amount of data to be processed and may therefore filter out information that may be regarded as less relevant, while preserving the important structural properties of an image.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] If the edge detection step is successful, the subsequent task of interpreting the information contents in the original image may therefore be substantially simplified.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] However, it is not always possible to obtain such ideal edges from real life images of moderate complexity.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Edge detection is one of the fundamental steps in image processing, image analysis, image pattern recognition, and computer vision techniques.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The edges extracted from a two-dimensional image of a three-dimensional scene can be classified as either viewpoint dependent or viewpoint independent.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A *viewpoint independent edge* typically reflects inherent properties of the three-dimensional objects, such as surface markings and surface shape.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A *viewpoint dependent edge* may change as the viewpoint changes, and typically reflects the geometry of the scene, such as objects occluding one another.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A typical edge might for instance be the border between a block of red color and a block of yellow.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] In contrast a **line** (as can be extracted by a ridge detector) can be a small number of pixels of a different color on an otherwise unchanging background.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] For a line, there may therefore usually be one edge on each side of the line.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Although certain literature has considered the detection of ideal step edges, the edges obtained from natural images are usually not at all ideal step edges.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A number of researchers have used a Gaussian smoothed step edge (an error function) as the simplest extension of the ideal step edge model for modeling the effects of edge blur in practical applications.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] At the left side of the edge, the intensity is $I_{\ell }=\lim _{x\rightarrow -\infty }f(x)$ , and right of the edge it is $I_{r}=\lim _{x\rightarrow \infty }f(x)$ .
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The scale parameter $\sigma$ is called the blur scale of the edge.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Ideally this scale parameter should be adjusted based on the quality of image to avoid destroying true edges of the image.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Outside of images with simple objects or featuring well-controlled lighting, edge detection is not a trivial task, since it can be difficult to determine what threshold should be used to define an edge between two pixels.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] However, if the intensity difference between the 4th and the 5th pixels were smaller, it would not be as easy to say that there should be an edge in the corresponding region.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Similarly, if the intensity differences between the adjacent neighboring pixels were higher, one could argue that more than one edge should be considered to exist, or even none at all.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] There are many methods for edge detection, but most of them can be grouped into two categories, search-based and zero-crossing based.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The zero-crossing based methods search for zero crossings in a second-order derivative expression computed from the image in order to find edges, usually the zero-crossings of the Laplacian or the zero-crossings of a non-linear differential expression.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] As a pre-processing step to edge detection, a smoothing stage, typically Gaussian smoothing, is almost always applied (see also noise reduction).
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The edge detection methods that have been published mainly differ in the types of smoothing filters that are applied and the way the measures of edge strength are computed.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] As many edge detection methods rely on the computation of image gradients, they also differ in the types of filters used for computing gradient estimates in the *x*- and *y*-directions.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A survey of a number of different edge detection methods can be found in (Ziou and Tabbone 1998); see also the encyclopedia articles on edge detection in *Encyclopedia of Mathematics* and Encyclopedia of Computer Science and Engineering.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] John Canny considered the mathematical problem of deriving an optimal smoothing filter, given the criteria of detection, localization and minimizing multiple responses to a single edge.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] He showed that the optimal filter, given these assumptions, is a sum of four exponential terms.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] He also showed that this filter can be well approximated by first-order derivatives of Gaussians.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Canny also introduced the notion of non-maximum suppression, which means that, given the presmoothing filters, edge points are defined as points where the gradient magnitude assumes a local maximum in the gradient direction.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Looking for the zero crossing of the 2nd derivative along the gradient direction was first proposed by Haralick.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] It took less than two decades to find a modern geometric variational meaning for that operator, that links it to the Marr–Hildreth (zero crossing of the Laplacian) edge detector.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] That observation was presented by Ron Kimmel and Alfred Bruckstein.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Although his work was done in the early days of computer vision, the Canny edge detector (including its variations) is still a state-of-the-art edge detector.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Edge detectors that perform better than the Canny usually require longer computation times or a greater number of parameters.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Kovalevsky has suggested a quite different approach.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] He uses a preprocessing of the image with the Sigma filter and with a special filter for the dilution of the ramps.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This method uses no brightness of the image but only the intensities of the color channels which is important for detecting an edge between two adjacent pixels of equal brightness but different colors.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The method scans the image two times: first along the horizontal lines and second along the vertical columns.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] In each horizontal line six consequent adjacent pixels are considered and five color difference between each two adjacent pixels are calculated.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Each color difference is the sum of absolute differences of the intensities of the color channels Red, Green, and Blue of the corresponding adjacent pixels.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] If this sum is greater than a given threshold, then the sign of the color difference is set equal to the sign of the difference of the green intensities.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] If the green difference is zero, then the sign of the color difference is set equal to the sign of the difference of the red intensities.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] If, however, both the green and the red differences are zero, then the sign of the color difference is set equal to the sign of the blue difference which in this case cannot be zero since the sum is greater than the threshold.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Certain conditions for the values and signs of the five color differences are specified in such way that if the conditions are fulfilled, then a short vertical stroke is put between the third and the fourth of the six pixels as the label of the edge.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Similar calculations are performed for the vertical columns.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] In this case a short horizontal stroke is put between the third and the fourth of the six subsequent pixels.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The vertical and horizontal strokes (being the one-dimensional cells of an abstract cell complex corresponding to the image) mostly compose a connected sequence representing the edge.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This method is robust and very fast and, what is more important, it can detect edges between adjacent pixels of equal brightness’s if the color difference between these pixels is greater than the threshold.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The Canny–Deriche detector was derived from similar mathematical criteria as the Canny edge detector, although starting from a discrete viewpoint and then leading to a set of recursive filters for image smoothing instead of exponential filters or Gaussian filters.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The differential edge detector described below can be seen as a reformulation of Canny's method from the viewpoint of differential invariants computed from a scale space representation leading to a number of advantages in terms of both theoretical analysis and sub-pixel implementation.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] In that aspect, Log Gabor filter have been shown to be a good choice to extract boundaries in natural scenes.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Different gradient operators can be applied to estimate image gradients from the input image or a smoothed version of it.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Other first-order difference operators for estimating image gradient have been proposed in the Prewitt operator, Roberts cross, Kayyali operator and Frei–Chen operator.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] It is possible to extend filters dimension to avoid the issue of recognizing edge in low SNR image.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The cost of this operation is loss in terms of resolution.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Once we have computed a measure of edge strength (typically the gradient magnitude), the next stage is to apply a threshold, to decide whether edges are present or not at an image point.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The lower the threshold, the more edges will be detected, and the result will be increasingly susceptible to noise and detecting edges of irrelevant features in the image.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Conversely a high threshold may miss subtle edges, or result in fragmented edges.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] If the edge is applied to just the gradient magnitude image, the resulting edges will in general be thick and some type of edge thinning post-processing is necessary.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] For edges detected with non-maximum suppression however, the edge curves are thin by definition and the edge pixels can be linked into edge polygon by an edge linking (edge tracking) procedure.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A commonly used approach to handle the problem of appropriate thresholds for thresholding is by using thresholding with hysteresis.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This method uses multiple thresholds to find edges.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] We begin by using the upper threshold to find the start of an edge.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Once we have a start point, we then trace the path of the edge through the image pixel by pixel, marking an edge whenever we are above the lower threshold.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] We stop marking our edge only when the value falls below our lower threshold.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This approach makes the assumption that edges are likely to be in continuous curves, and allows us to follow a faint section of an edge we have previously seen, without meaning that every noisy pixel in the image is marked down as an edge.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Still, however, we have the problem of choosing appropriate thresholding parameters, and suitable thresholding values may vary over the image.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This method finds connected set of pixels having a directional derivative magnitude larger than a fairly small threshold.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] It considers only presence of gradients instead of strength of gradients.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] After applying a dramatically small threshold (i.e.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The morphological opening operation and the morphological closing operation are applied to the binary image to close gaps.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Then, the distance transform operation is applied to the binary image to clear the pixels far from the background, so blob-like shapes or other false labeled regions are deleted from the edge map.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Edge thinning is a technique used to remove the unwanted spurious points on the edges in an image.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This technique is employed after the image has been filtered for noise (using median, Gaussian filter etc.), the edge operator has been applied (like the ones described above, Canny or Sobel) to detect the edges and after the edges have been smoothed using an appropriate threshold value.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This removes all the unwanted points, and if applied carefully, results in one pixel thick edge elements.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] If Hough transforms are used to detect lines and ellipses, then thinning could give much better results.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] If the edge happens to be the boundary of a region, then thinning could easily give the image parameters like perimeter without much algebra.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] 8 connectivity is preferred, where all the immediate pixels surrounding a particular pixel are considered.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Remove points from North, south, east and west.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Do this in multiple passes, i.e. after the north pass, use the same semi processed image in the other passes and so on.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Remove a point if: The point has no neighbors in the North (if you are in the north pass, and respective directions for other passes).
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Removing the points will not cause to disconnect its neighbors in any way.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The number of passes across direction should be chosen according to the level of accuracy desired.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Some edge-detection operators are instead based upon second-order derivatives of the intensity.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This essentially captures the rate of change in the intensity gradient.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Thus, in the ideal continuous case, detection of zero-crossings in the second derivative captures local maxima in the gradient.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The early Marr–Hildreth operator is based on the detection of zero-crossings of the Laplacian operator applied to a Gaussian-smoothed image.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] It can be shown, however, that this operator will also return false edges corresponding to local minima of the gradient magnitude.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Moreover, this operator will give poor localization at curved edges.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Hence, this operator is today mainly of historical interest.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Following the differential geometric way of expressing the requirement of non-maximum suppression proposed by Lindeberg, let us introduce at every image point a local coordinate system $(u,v)$ , with the v -direction parallel to the gradient direction.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] where $L_{x},L_{y},\ldots ,L_{yyy}$ denote partial derivatives computed from a scale space representation L obtained by smoothing the original image with a Gaussian kernel.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] In this way, the edges will be automatically obtained as continuous curves with sub-pixel accuracy.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Hysteresis thresholding can also be applied to these differential and subpixel edge segments.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Higher-order derivatives for the third-order sign condition can be obtained in an analogous fashion.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A recent development in edge detection techniques takes a frequency domain approach to finding edge locations.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Phase congruency (also known as phase coherence) methods attempt to find locations in an image where all sinusoids in the frequency domain are in phase.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] These locations will generally correspond to the location of a perceived edge, regardless of whether the edge is represented by a large change in intensity in the spatial domain.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A key benefit of this technique is that it responds strongly to Mach bands, and avoids false positives typically found around roof edges.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] A roof edge, is a discontinuity in the first order derivative of a grey-level profile.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The phase stretch transform or PST is a physics-inspired computational approach to signal and image processing.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] One of its utilities is for feature detection and classification.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] PST is a spin-off from research on the time stretch dispersive Fourier transform.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] PST transforms the image by emulating propagation through a diffractive medium with engineered 3D dispersive property (refractive index).
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The operation relies on symmetry of the dispersion profile and can be understood in terms of dispersive eigenfunctions or stretch modes.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] PST performs similar functionality as phase contrast microscopy but on digital images.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] PST is also applicable to digital images as well as temporal, time series, data.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] To increase the precision of edge detection, several subpixel techniques had been proposed, including curve-fitting, moment-based, reconstructive, and partial area effect methods.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] These methods have different characteristics.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Curve fitting methods are computationally simple but are easily affected by noise.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Moment-based methods use an integral-based approach to reduce the effect of noise, but may require more computations in some cases.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Reconstructive methods use horizontal gradients or vertical gradients to build a curve and find the peak of the curve as the sub-pixel edge.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Partial area effect methods are based on the hypothesis that each pixel value depends on the area at both sides of the edge inside that pixel, producing accurate individual estimation for every edge pixel.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Certain variants of the moment-based technique have been shown to be the most accurate for isolated edges.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The Marr-Hildreth edge detector is distinguished by its use of the Laplacian of Gaussian (LoG) operator for edge detection in digital images.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Unlike other edge detection methods, the LoG approach combines Gaussian smoothing with second derivative operations, allowing for simultaneous noise reduction and edge enhancement.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] The key advantage of this method lies in its ability to detect edges at various scales by adjusting the standard deviation of the Gaussian kernel, enabling detection of fine details as well as broader transitions.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] Moreover, the technique leverages zero-crossing detection on the LoG response to precisely locate edges, offering robustness against noise and maintaining edge continuity.
[src:focus-peaking/edge-detection] This approach is particularly effective for detecting edges with clear boundaries in images while minimizing false positives due to noise, making it a valuable tool in computer vision applications where accurate edge localization is crucial.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] An **electronic viewfinder** (**EVF**) is a camera viewfinder where the image captured by the lens is displayed on a small screen (usually LCD or OLED) which the photographer can look through when composing their shot.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] It differs from a live preview screen in being smaller and shaded from ambient light, and may also use less power.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] The sensor records the view through the lens, the view is processed, and finally projected on a miniature display which is viewable through the eyepiece.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] Digital viewfinders are used in digital still cameras and in video cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] Some cameras (such as Panasonic, Sony, Fujifilm) have an automatic eye sensor which switches the display from screen to EVF when the viewfinder is near the eye.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] More modest cameras use a button to switch the display.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] While many cameras come with a built-in EVF, this is fixed in place and can only be used while holding the camera to the user's eye, which may not be convenient.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] Other cameras don't come with an EVF at all, or come with a low quality one.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] It is sometimes possible to get a separate, attachable EVF to use in these cases.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] In certain higher end models such as the Alexa Series by ARRI, an external viewfinder is the default way of monitoring what is being shot.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] Whereas EVFs use a digital screen to display a representation of the scene captured by a camera, an optical viewfinder (OVF) typically uses a prism and mirror to direct the image coming through the camera's lens to the viewfinder.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] An EVF enables the user to view previously taken photographs and use the camera's menu system while looking through the viewfinder, which is not possible with an OVF.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] The digital preview shown in an EVF incorporates the camera's settings (including exposure, white balance, etc.) and so the image seen can be an exact preview of what the taken photograph will look like, which is not possible with an OVF.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] OVFs may be better suited to use in low light or situations with very big differences in brightness due to the dynamic range limitations of an electronic screen.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] There is also no time lag with an OVF, whereas an EVF might take a bit of time to process the image and update the display (particularly when using longer exposure times).
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] To get the advantage of both optical and digital viewfinders some cameras have hybrid viewfinders.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] These display the image in an optical eyepiece viewfinder, or digitally on an LCD screen.
[src:focus-peaking/electronic-viewfinder] Examples include some Fujifilm X-series cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] An **image organizer** or **image management application** is application software for organising digital images.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] It is a kind of desktop organizer software application.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Image organizer software focuses on handling large numbers of images.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] In contrast to an image viewer, an image organizer can edit image tags and can often upload files to on-line hosting pages.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Enterprises may use Digital Asset Management (DAM) solutions to manage larger and broader amounts of digital media.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Some programs that come with desktop environments, such as gThumb (GNOME) and digiKam (KDE) were originally simple image viewers, and have evolved into image organizers.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Many commercial image organizers offer both automatic and manual image organization features.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] A comparison of image viewers reveals that many free software packages are available that offer most of the organization features available in commercial software.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Supports: >100 file formats, Unicode, batch processing, viewing contents of archives formats, non-destructive editing, DB export, R/W to CD, VCD, DVD.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Contains: SMTP email client, FTP transport, duplicate file finder.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Professional image management application database, asynchronously catalog DVD collections of 10,000's of photos.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Also supports management and sharing of video clips.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Team features such as version control and activity logging.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Support for very large collections (millions).
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Integrated with Google online tool suite.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Default photo manager for macOS, iOS, tvOS, watchOS.
[src:focus-peaking/image-organisation] Default photo manager for Windows 8 and later.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The concept for cameras with live preview largely derives from electronic (video) TV cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Until 1995 most digital cameras did not have live preview, and it was more than ten years after this that the higher end digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLR) adopted this feature, as it is fundamentally incompatible with the swinging-mirror single-lens reflex mechanism.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The first digital still camera with an LCD for autogain framing live preview was the Casio QV-10 in 1995.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The first prosumer camera to use live view for both exposure simulation live preview ES-LV control and live preview framing was the fixed-lens Canon PowerShot G1 from 2000 (possibly the first was Canon Powershot Pro70 in 1998), although this was still in the line of compact cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The first DSLR to use live view for framing preview only, like early other live view but non-mirrored digicams, was the fixed-lens Olympus E-10 from 2000.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The first interchangeable-lens DSLR to use a live preview for framing was the Fujifilm FinePix S3 Pro, which was launched in October 2004.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Its "Live Image" mode could display a live, black-and-white framing preview of the subject that could be magnified for manual focusing purposes, although the preview was limited to a duration of thirty seconds.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The first general-use interchangeable-lens DSLRs with live view for both exposure simulated live preview (ExpSim LV) and framing livepreview were the Canon 20Da of 2005, followed by Canon EOS 1Ds Mark III and Canon EOS 40D of 2007.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The first general-use interchangeable-lens DSLR with live view for framing preview only like most fixed lens digicams was the Olympus E-330 of 2006.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] There are two distinct modes of live-preview, with only a few manufacturers offering both in their digital cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The first is a more rudimentary type of live preview that displays the overall framing on an electronic display and allows a preview of what the camera's sensor will detect before the photograph is taken.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] This can be particularly helpful when the lighting conditions are too dark for an optical viewfinder.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] This type of live preview is the *autogain/framing* live view type (or *framing priority display*).
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] This requires traditional means of exposure determination requiring metering of the light coming through the lens, and interpreting the light intensity indication on an automatic light meter, and then adjusting exposure parameters for a desired effect.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The second is a more sophisticated type of live preview that displays the exact exposure 'look' on an electronic display and allows the photographer to alter the exposure look via adjustments to parameters such as shutter speed, film speed or ISO, and aperture, before the photograph is taken.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] This second type of live preview is the *exposure simulation* live preview type (or *exposure priority display*).
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] This type of live preview eliminates reliance on traditional light metering usage.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Many modern bridge and compact cameras with movie mode have only an automatic exposure and limited exposure compensation control, and live view that is primarily for framing only.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Live-preview-only cameras, that is cameras without an optical viewfinder, include four different categories: compact digital cameras, bridge digital cameras, and the newer mirrorless interchangeable lens cameras and Sony SLT cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Bridge cameras in general are higher-end, that is they contain more advanced features, better build quality, larger size, and are more expensive than compacts, but retain a small digital sensor.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Mirrorless cameras feature a larger sensor and interchangeable lenses, like DSLRs, but sacrifice the SLR mirror mechanism and viewfinder to save size and cost, and hence only offer live preview.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The SLT, developed by Sony, uses a mirror similar to that found in a DSLR.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] However, unlike the moving and fully reflective mirror of DSLRs, the SLT mirror is fixed and semi-reflective.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The same technology was used by Olympus prior to Sony in the Olympus E-10.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] This gives a live real-time WYSIWYG (what you see is what you get) exposure simulation preview in Full Manual / Manual ISO mode, and Auto-Exposure (AE) / Manual ISO modes: P (Program), TV (Time Value: shutter speed priority), and Av (Aperture Value).
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] If Auto ISO is used, Autogain (Auto-EV0) framing/focus live view suspends Exposure Simulation live view.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Later, Canon extended its more sophisticated DSLR ExpSim LV all shooting light conditions like its Powershot digicams.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The most significant advances and difference in DSLR version of ES-LV was simulating exposure changes effects with chosen aperture changes without stopping down the aperture.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The ES-LV of its Powershot digicams always kept its apertures stopped down, so no 'aperture exposure simulation' was needed, and briefly opened aperture to assess focus with shutter button partially depressed before a shot is taken.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The ExpSim LV of its EOS lens DSLRs could achieve the same 'exposure simulation' effect in both aperture stop-down mode and aperture wide open of its EOS lenses, even if the aperture selection was narrower than widest diameter (wide open).
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The time saved assessing instant optimal exposure choices for any new or changing lit scenario, freed the ExpSim LV DSLR users to spend all their time shooting primarily with their optical viewfinder (OVF).
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The first interchangeable-lens DSLR to feature framing live preview was the 2004 Fujifilm FinePix S3 Pro.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] While initially largely a novelty feature, framing/focus only live-preview functionality from digicam framing/focus live view has become more common on DSLR cameras, and almost all new DSLRs have had the feature since mid-2008.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] This is particularly the case since the advent of movie mode common to digicam video features on these cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The principal function of live preview on Canon DSLRs from the 20Da onwards has been to allow, via LCD viewing, rapid acquisition of consistent and predictable exposure selection before taking a photograph via its 'exposure simulation' (ExpSim) enabled mode, or exposure priority display.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Real-time exposure simulation live preview (or exposure priority display) had been available in many prosumer cameras, such as the Canon PowerShot G series, before being available to in live view DSLRs.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Some manufacturers of compact cameras, including prosumer models, still lack this exposure simulation live view feature, instead relying on the more rudimentary autogain/framing only live view, where slow focus and slow exposure estimation via TTL metering techniques are relied upon.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Real-time exposure simulation capable live preview digital cameras make achieving the desired exposures, especially in manual modes, more quickly available for both still and video photography.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Among the DSLRs that do manage to focus using the standard phase-detection sensors used by DSLRs, unlike some compact digital cameras none has managed to show 100% frame coverage.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] This removes one of the key advantages of live preview over optical viewfinders, especially on more budget cameras.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Additionally, 100% coverage optical viewfinders have recently become more common and affordable with the appearance of the Canon EOS 7D, Nikon D300, Olympus E-3 and the Pentax K-7.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Still more recently, the (upper) mid-range Nikon D7000 has brought the feature to a somewhat lower price point.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Some real-time exposure simulated capable live preview digital cameras also offer live histogram graphs for tonal balance or color, where the graph changes instantaneously as exposure adjustments are made.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Almost all modern bridge and compact cameras have a movie mode, while this feature only became available on DSLRs during 2008.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The Nikon D90 with 720p video was announced in August 2008, and the Canon EOS 5D Mark II with 1080p video was announced in September 2008.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] The Canon EOS 5D Mark II was the first DSLR to offer full control over its real-time exposure simulation live preview for video, rather than just autogain/framing only live preview.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Live preview can show additional information, such as an image histogram, focal ratio, camera settings, battery charge, and remaining storage space.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Some implementations have a focus peaking feature that highlights areas of the frame that are in focus.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Live preview has been in use with bridge cameras for some years but with limited resolution and image quality.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] They are used in most mirrorless modern system cameras (e.g.
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Panasonic Micro Four Third System, Sony NEX, Sony SLT, Nikon V1).
[src:focus-peaking/live-preview] Many professional photographers and advanced amateurs prefer DSLR cameras that have a true optical through-the-lens viewfinder (OVF).
